    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-08-05T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-08-05T02:00:00-05:00" n="52"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d52">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.8890/9732/6: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Afghanistan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Engert</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Kabul</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-08-05T11:00:00+04:00"
                            >August 5, 1942—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received August 6—9:48 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>48. The Legation has been requested by the Ministry of Foreign Affairs both
                    orally and in writing to assist it in obtaining shipping space from Karachi to
                    the United States for approximately 900 bales of karakul, 100 bales furs, 250
                    tons of wool and 40 tons pistachio nuts, all of which are now lying at Karachi.
                    Ministry states that efforts made through Afghan Consul in New York have proved
                    fruitless and points out that karakul is an extremely important item in
                    Afghanistan’s foreign trade and that the United States is now the only market
                    open to it. It hopes that in order to strengthen trade <pb facs="0066" n="54"
                        xml:id="pg_54"/> relations between the two countries the above and some
                    similar shipments in the future may be accepted.</p>
                <p>We have of course carefully explained the policy of the United States
                    necessitated by the exigencies of the war and have referred to its circular of
                    July 3.<note n="15" xml:id="d52fn15">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>[<signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Engert</hi>
                    </signed>]</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
